{{

      "field": "start_tstamp",
      "data_type": "timestamp"
    }),
    cluster_by=snowplow_utils.get_value_by_target_type(bigquery_val=["device_user_id"]),
    sort='device_user_id',

select
  device_user_id,
  -- time
  user_start_tstamp as start_tstamp,
  user_end_tstamp as end_tstamp,
  -- first/last session. Max to resolve edge case with multiple sessions with the same start/end tstamp
  {% if target.type == 'postgres' %}
    cast(max(case when start_tstamp = user_start_tstamp then cast(session_id as {{ type_string() }} ) end) as {{type_string()}}) as first_session_id,
    cast(max(case when end_tstamp = user_end_tstamp then cast(session_id as {{ type_string() }} ) end) as {{type_string()}}) as last_session_id,
  {% else %}
    max(case when start_tstamp = user_start_tstamp then session_id end) as first_session_id,
    max(case when end_tstamp = user_end_tstamp then session_id end) as last_session_id,
  {% endif %}
  -- engagement
  sum(screen_views) as screen_views,
  sum(screen_names_viewed) as screen_names_viewed,
  count(distinct session_id) as sessions,
  sum(session_duration_s) as sessions_duration_s,
  count(distinct {{ date_trunc('day', 'start_tstamp') }}) as active_days,
  sum(app_errors) as app_errors,
  sum(fatal_app_errors) as fatal_app_errors

from {{ ref('snowplow_mobile_users_sessions_this_run') }}

group by 1,2,3

model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_sc.name: snowplow_mobile_screen_views_this_run
model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_sc.description: This staging table contains all the screen views for the given run of the mobile model. It possess all the same columns as `snowplow_mobile_screen_views`. If building a custom module that requires screen view events, this is the table you should reference.

screen_view_id.name: screen_view_id
screen_view_id.description: The UUID of a screen view.

event_id.name: event_id
event_id.description: A UUID for each event e.g. `c6ef3124-b53a-4b13-a233-0088f79dcbcb`.

app_id.name: app_id
app_id.description: Application ID e.g. `angry-birds` is used to distinguish different applications that are being tracked by the same Snowplow stack, e.g. production versus dev.

user_id.name: user_id
user_id.description: Unique ID set by business e.g. `jon.doe@email.com`.

network_userid.name: network_userid
network_userid.description: User ID set by Snowplow using 3rd party cookie e.g. `ecdff4d0-9175-40ac-a8bb-325c49733607`.

previous_session_id.name: previous_session_id
previous_session_id.description: A previous visit / session index e.g. `3`.

session_first_event_id.name: session_first_event_id
session_first_event_id.description: A first visit / session index e.g. `3`.

screen_view_in_session_index.name: screen_view_in_session_index
screen_view_in_session_index.description: The index of the screen view within the session. This is generated by the tracker.

screen_views_in_session.name: screen_views_in_session
screen_views_in_session.description: Total number of screen views within a session.

dvce_created_tstamp.name: dvce_created_tstamp
dvce_created_tstamp.description: Timestamp event was recorded on the client device e.g. `2013-11-26 00:03:57.885`.

collector_tstamp.name: collector_tstamp
collector_tstamp.description: Time stamp for the event recorded by the collector e.g. `2013-11-26 00:02:05`.

derived_tstamp.name: derived_tstamp
derived_tstamp.description: Timestamp making allowance for innaccurate device clock e.g. `2013-11-26 00:02:04`.

model_tstamp.name: model_tstamp
model_tstamp.description: The current timestamp when the model processed this row.

screen_view_transition_type.name: screen_view_transition_type

screen_view_type.name: screen_view_type
screen_view_type.description: The type of screen that was viewed.

screen_fragment.name: screen_fragment

screen_top_view_controller.name: screen_top_view_controller
screen_top_view_controller.description: The name of the root view controller.

screen_view_controller.name: screen_view_controller
screen_view_controller.description: The name of the view controller.

screen_view_previous_id.name: screen_view_previous_id
screen_view_previous_id.description: The UUID of the previous screen view.

screen_view_previous_name.name: screen_view_previous_name
screen_view_previous_name.description: The name of the previous screen view.

screen_view_previous_type.name: screen_view_previous_type
screen_view_previous_type.description: The type of the previous screen viewed.

device_manufacturer.name: device_manufacturer
device_manufacturer.description: Manufacturer name of the device eg. `Apple`.

os_type.name: os_type
os_type.description: Type of OS running on the mobile device.

android_idfa.name: android_idfa
android_idfa.description: Identifier for Advertisers for Android devices.

apple_idfa.name: apple_idfa

with screen_views_dedupe as (
  select
    ev.screen_view_id,
    ev.event_id,

    ev.app_id,

    ev.user_id,

    ev.derived_tstamp,

    ev.screen_view_name,
    ev.screen_view_transition_type,
    ev.screen_view_type,
    ev.screen_fragment,
    ev.screen_top_view_controller,
    ev.screen_view_controller,
    ev.screen_view_previous_id,
    ev.screen_view_previous_name,
    ev.screen_view_previous_type,

    ev.platform,
    ev.dvce_screenwidth,
    ev.dvce_screenheight,
    ev.device_manufacturer,
    ev.device_model,
    ev.os_type,
    ev.os_version,
    ev.android_idfa,
    ev.apple_idfa,
    ev.apple_idfv,
    ev.carrier,
    ev.open_idfa,
    ev.network_technology,
    ev.network_type,

    ev.device_latitude,
    ev.device_longitude,
    ev.device_latitude_longitude_accuracy,
    ev.device_altitude,
    ev.device_altitude_accuracy,
    ev.device_bearing,
    ev.device_speed,
    ev.geo_country,
    ev.geo_region,
    ev.geo_city,
    ev.geo_zipcode,
    ev.geo_latitude,
    ev.geo_longitude,
    ev.geo_region_name,
    ev.geo_timezone,

    ev.user_ipaddress,

    ev.useragent,

    ev.build,
    ev.version,

    row_number() over (partition by ev.screen_view_id order by ev.derived_tstamp) as screen_view_id_index

    {%- if var('snowplow__screen_view_passthroughs', []) -%}
      {%- set passthrough_names = [] -%}
      {%- for identifier in var('snowplow__screen_view_passthroughs', []) %}
      {# Check if it's a simple column or a sql+alias #}
        {%- if identifier is mapping -%}
          ,{{identifier['sql']}} as {{identifier['alias']}}
          {%- do passthrough_names.append(identifier['alias']) -%}
        {%- else -%}
          ,ev.{{identifier}}
          {%- do passthrough_names.append(identifier) -%}
        {%- endif -%}
      {% endfor -%}
  {%- endif %}

  from {{ ref('snowplow_mobile_base_events_this_run') }} as ev

  where ev.event_name = 'screen_view'
  and ev.screen_view_id is not null
)

  )

  ev.os_type,
  ev.os_version,
  ev.android_idfa,
  ev.apple_idfa,
  ev.apple_idfv,
  ev.open_idfa,
  ev.carrier,
  ev.network_technology,
  ev.network_type,

  ev.device_latitude,
  ev.device_longitude,
  ev.device_latitude_longitude_accuracy,
  ev.device_altitude,
  ev.device_altitude_accuracy,
  ev.device_bearing,
  ev.device_speed,
  ev.geo_country,
  ev.geo_region,
  ev.geo_city,
  ev.geo_zipcode,
  ev.geo_latitude,
  ev.geo_longitude,
  ev.geo_region_name,
  ev.geo_timezone,

  ev.user_ipaddress,

  {%- if var('snowplow__screen_view_passthroughs', []) -%}

  {%- endif %}

from cleaned_screen_view_events ev

model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.name: snowplow_mobile_base_sessions_this_run
model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.description: For any given run, this table contains all the required sessions.
model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.compiled_code:
select
        s.session_identifier,
        s.user_identifier,
        s.start_tstamp,
        -- end_tstamp used in next step to limit events. When backfilling, set end_tstamp to upper_limit if end_tstamp > upper_limit.
        -- This ensures we don't accidentally process events after upper_limit
        case when s.end_tstamp > 
        cast('2021-11-05 00:00:00' as timestamp)
     then 
        cast('2021-11-05 00:00:00' as timestamp)
     else s.end_tstamp end as end_tstamp

        from SNOWPLOW_DEV1.gh_sp_mobile_dbt_1_snowplow_manifest.snowplow_mobile_base_sessions_lifecycle_manifest s

        where
        -- General window of start_tstamps to limit table scans. Logic complicated by backfills.
        -- To be within the run, session start_tstamp must be >= lower_limit - max_session_days as we limit end_tstamp in manifest to start_tstamp + max_session_days
        s.start_tstamp >= 
        cast('2021-03-04 00:00:00' as timestamp)
    
        and s.start_tstamp <= 
        cast('2021-11-05 00:00:00' as timestamp)
    
        -- Select sessions within window that either; start or finish between lower & upper limit, start and finish outside of lower and upper limits
        and not (s.start_tstamp > 
        cast('2021-11-05 00:00:00' as timestamp)
     or s.end_tstamp < 
        cast('2021-03-07 00:00:00' as timestamp)
    )

model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.name: snowplow_mobile_base_new_event_limits
model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.description:
This table contains the lower and upper timestamp limits for the given run of the mobile model. These limits are used to select new events from the events table.

The sql to determine the correct limits for the run is generated by the `get_run_limits()` macro. Please refer to the documentation for details on how this macro determines the run limits.

lower_limit.name: lower_limit
lower_limit.description: The lower `collector_tstamp` limit for the run

upper_limit.name: upper_limit
upper_limit.description: The upper `collector_tstamp` limit for the run

model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.compiled_code:
select
        

    dateadd(
        hour,
        -6,
        
        cast('2021-04-21 13:50:44.234000' as timestamp)
    
        )

 as lower_limit,
        least(

    dateadd(
        day,
        20,
        
        cast('2021-04-21 13:50:44.234000' as timestamp)
    
        )

,
              
    convert_timezone('UTC', convert_timezone('UTC', current_timestamp()))::timestamp
) as upper_limit

model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.name: snowplow_mobile_base_events_this_run
model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.description:
For any given run, this table contains all required events to be consumed by subsequent nodes in the Snowplow dbt mob package. This is a cleaned, de-duped dataset, containing all columns from the raw events table as well as having various optional contexts joined-on/unpacked.

**Note: This table should be used as the input to any custom modules that require event level data, rather than selecting straight from `atomic.events`**

screen_view_controller.name: screen_view_controller
screen_view_controller.description: The name of the view controller.

device_manufacturer.name: device_manufacturer

os_type.name: os_type
os_type.description: Type of OS running on the mobile device.

android_idfa.name: android_idfa
android_idfa.description: Identifier for Advertisers for Android devices.

apple_idfa.name: apple_idfa
apple_idfa.description: Identifier for Advertisers for Apple devices.

apple_idfv.name: apple_idfv
apple_idfv.description: Identifier for Vendors for Apple devices.

device_latitude_longitude_accuracy.name: device_latitude_longitude_accuracy
device_latitude_longitude_accuracy.description: Accuracy of Latitude and Longitude coordinates for device location.

device_bearing.name: device_bearing
device_bearing.description: Horizontal angle between device and true north.

previous_session_id.name: previous_session_id
previous_session_id.description: A previous visit / session index e.g. `3`.

session_first_event_id.name: session_first_event_id
session_first_event_id.description: A first visit / session index e.g. `3`.

app_id.name: app_id
app_id.description: Application ID e.g. `angry-birds` is used to distinguish different applications that are being tracked by the same Snowplow stack, e.g. production versus dev.

collector_tstamp.name: collector_tstamp
collector_tstamp.description: Time stamp for the event recorded by the collector e.g. `2013-11-26 00:02:05`.

dvce_created_tstamp.name: dvce_created_tstamp
dvce_created_tstamp.description: Timestamp event was recorded on the client device e.g. `2013-11-26 00:03:57.885`.

event.name: event
event.description: The type of event recorded e.g. `page_view`.

event_id.name: event_id
event_id.description: A UUID for each event e.g. `c6ef3124-b53a-4b13-a233-0088f79dcbcb`.

user_id.name: user_id
user_id.description: Unique ID set by business e.g. `jon.doe@email.com`.

network_userid.name: network_userid
network_userid.description: User ID set by Snowplow using 3rd party cookie e.g. `ecdff4d0-9175-40ac-a8bb-325c49733607`.

geo_country.name: geo_country
geo_country.description: ISO 3166-1 code for the country the visitor is located in e.g. `GB`, `US`.

geo_region.name: geo_region
geo_region.description: ISO-3166-2 code for country region the visitor is in e.g. `I9`, `TX`.

geo_zipcode.description: Postcode the visitor is in e.g. `94109`.

ip_domain.description: Second level domain name associated with the visitor's IP address e.g. `nuvox.net`.

se_label.description: The object of the action e.g. the ID of the video played or SKU of the product added-to-basket e.g. `pbz00123`.

se_property.name: se_property
se_property.description: A property associated with the object of the action e.g. `HD`, `large`.

derived_tstamp.name: derived_tstamp
derived_tstamp.description: Timestamp making allowance for innaccurate device clock e.g. `2013-11-26 00:02:04`.

true_tstamp.name: true_tstamp
true_tstamp.description: User-set “true timestamp” for the event e.g. `2013-11-26 00:02:04`.

event_id_dedupe_index.description: An indexing column used for de-duplication of raw events

,NULL

                e.*
                

            from SNOWPLOW_DEV1.gh_sp_mobile_dbt_1_snplw_mobile_int_tests.snowplow_mobile_events_stg e

            b.user_identifier -- take user_identifier from manifest. This ensures only 1 domain_userid per session.

        inner join SNOWPLOW_DEV1.gh_sp_mobile_dbt_1_scratch.snowplow_mobile_base_sessions_this_run as b
        on a.session_identifier = b.session_identifier

model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.name: snowplow_mobile_base_sessions_lifecycle_manifest
model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.description:
This incremental table is a manifest of all sessions that have been processed by the Snowplow dbt mobile model. For each session, the start and end timestamp is recorded.

By knowing the life-cycle of a session the model is able to able to determine which sessions and thus events to process for a given time-frame, as well as the complete date range required to reprocess all events of each session.

model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_ba.compiled_code:
with new_events_session_ids_init as (
            select
            
                COALESCE(
                    
e.contexts_com_snowplowanalytics_snowplow_client_session_1[0]:sessionId::TEXT
,NULL
                ) as session_identifier,
                max(
                    COALESCE(
                        
e.contexts_com_snowplowanalytics_snowplow_client_session_1[0]:userId::TEXT
,NULL
                    )
                ) as user_identifier, -- Edge case 1: Arbitary selection to avoid window function like first_value.
            
                min(collector_tstamp) as start_tstamp,
                max(collector_tstamp) as end_tstamp

            from SNOWPLOW_DEV1.gh_sp_mobile_dbt_1_snplw_mobile_int_tests.snowplow_mobile_events_stg e

            where
                dvce_sent_tstamp <= 

    dateadd(
        day,
        3,
        dvce_created_tstamp
        )

 -- don't process data that's too late
                and collector_tstamp >= 
        cast('2021-03-07 00:00:00' as timestamp)
    
                and collector_tstamp <= 
        cast('2021-11-05 00:00:00' as timestamp)
    
                and true
                and cast(True as boolean) --don't reprocess sessions that have already been processed.
                

            group by 1
        ), new_events_session_ids as (
            select *
            from new_events_session_ids_init e
            

        )
        

        , previous_sessions as (
        select *

        from SNOWPLOW_DEV1.gh_sp_mobile_dbt_1_snowplow_manifest.snowplow_mobile_base_sessions_lifecycle_manifest

        where start_tstamp >= 
        cast('2019-03-08 00:00:00' as timestamp)
    
        and cast(True as boolean) --don't reprocess sessions that have already been processed.
        )

        , session_lifecycle as (
        select
            ns.session_identifier,
            coalesce(self.user_identifier, ns.user_identifier) as user_identifier, -- Edge case 1: Take previous value to keep domain_userid consistent. Not deterministic but performant
            least(ns.start_tstamp, coalesce(self.start_tstamp, ns.start_tstamp)) as start_tstamp,
            greatest(ns.end_tstamp, coalesce(self.end_tstamp, ns.end_tstamp)) as end_tstamp -- BQ 1 NULL will return null hence coalesce

        from new_events_session_ids ns
        left join previous_sessions as self
            on ns.session_identifier = self.session_identifier

        where
            self.session_identifier is null -- process all new sessions
            or self.end_tstamp < 

    dateadd(
        day,
        3,
        self.start_tstamp
        )

 --stop updating sessions exceeding 3 days
        )

        

        select
        sl.session_identifier,
        sl.user_identifier,
        sl.start_tstamp,
        least(

    dateadd(
        day,
        3,
        sl.start_tstamp
        )

, sl.end_tstamp) as end_tstamp -- limit session length to max_session_days
        

        from session_lifecycle sl
    

where session_identifier is not null

with events as (
  select
    es.session_id,
    es.event_id,
    es.event_name,
    es.derived_tstamp,
    es.build,
    es.version,
    es.event_index_in_session,
    MAX(es.event_index_in_session) over (partition by es.session_id) as events_in_session

  from {{ ref('snowplow_mobile_base_events_this_run') }}   es
)

, session_aggs AS (
  select
    e.session_id,
    --last dimensions
    MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then e.build end) as last_build,
    MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then e.version end) as last_version,
    MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then e.event_name end) as last_event_name,
    {% if target.type == 'postgres' %}
      cast(MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then cast(e.event_id as {{ type_string() }}) end) as {{ type_string() }}) as session_last_event_id,
    {% else %}
      MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then e.event_id end) as session_last_event_id,
    {% endif %}

    -- time
    MIN(e.derived_tstamp) as start_tstamp,
    MAX(e.derived_tstamp) as end_tstamp,
    {{ snowplow_mobile.bool_or("e.event_name = 'application_install'") }} as has_install

  from events e

  group by 1
)

, app_errors as (
  {% if var("snowplow__enable_app_errors_module", false) %}
    select
      ae.session_id,
      COUNT(distinct ae.event_id) AS app_errors,
      COUNT(distinct case when ae.is_fatal then ae.event_id end) as fatal_app_errors

    from {{ ref('snowplow_mobile_app_errors_this_run') }} ae

    group by 1
  {% else %}
    select
      cast(null as {{type_string() }}) as session_id,
      cast(null as {{ type_int() }}) as app_errors,
      cast(null as {{ type_int() }}) as fatal_app_errors
  {% endif %}
)


select
  sa.session_id,
  sa.last_build,
  sa.last_version,
  sa.last_event_name,
  sa.session_last_event_id,
  sa.start_tstamp,
  sa.end_tstamp,
  {{ snowplow_utils.timestamp_diff('sa.start_tstamp', 'sa.end_tstamp', 'second') }} as session_duration_s,
  sa.has_install,
  ae.app_errors,
  ae.fatal_app_errors

from session_aggs sa
left join app_errors ae
on sa.session_id = ae.session_id
model.snowplow_mobile.snowplow_mobile_se.compiled_code:
with events as (

    es.session_id,
    es.event_id,

    MAX(es.event_index_in_session) over (partition by es.session_id) as events_in_session

  from SNOWPLOW_DEV1.gh_sp_mobile_dbt_1_scratch.snowplow_mobile_base_events_this_run   es
)

, session_aggs AS (
  select
    e.session_id,
    --last dimensions
    MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then e.build end) as last_build,
    MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then e.version end) as last_version,
    MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then e.event_name end) as last_event_name,
    
      MAX(case when e.event_index_in_session = e.events_in_session then e.event_id end) as session_last_event_id,
    

    -- time
    MIN(e.derived_tstamp) as start_tstamp,
    MAX(e.derived_tstamp) as end_tstamp,
    

  BOOLOR_AGG(
    e.event_name = 'application_install'
  )

 as has_install

  from events e

  group by 1
)

, app_errors as (
  
    select
      cast(null as TEXT) as session_id,
      cast(null as integer) as app_errors,
      cast(null as integer) as fatal_app_errors
  
)


select
  sa.session_id,
  sa.last_build,
  sa.last_version,
  sa.last_event_name,
  sa.session_last_event_id,

  sa.end_tstamp,
  datediff(
        second,
        sa.start_tstamp,
        sa.end_tstamp

  sa.has_install,
  ae.app_errors,
  ae.fatal_app_errors

from session_aggs sa
left join app_errors ae
on sa.session_id = ae.session_id

root_id.name: root_id

root_tstamp.name: root_tstamp
root_tstamp.description: The timestamp for when this event was produced.

previous_session_id.description: A previous visit / session index e.g. `3`.

user_id.name: user_id
user_id.description: Unique ID set by business e.g. `jon.doe@email.com`.

first_event_id.name: first_event_id
first_event_id.description: The event ID of the first event.

id.name: id
id.description: A UUID for each row in the table.

source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.name: com_snowplowanalytics_snowplow_mobile_context_1
source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.description: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains various mobile device details and identifiers.

root_id.name: root_id
root_id.description: The corresponding UUID used in the root table.

root_tstamp.name: root_tstamp
root_tstamp.description: The timestamp for when this event was produced.

device_manufacturer.name: device_manufacturer
device_manufacturer.description: Manufacturer name of the device eg. `Apple`.

os_type.name: os_type
os_type.description: Type of OS running on the mobile device.

android_idfa.name: android_idfa
android_idfa.description: Identifier for Advertisers for Android devices.

apple_idfa.name: apple_idfa
apple_idfa.description: Identifier for Advertisers for Apple devices.

apple_idfv.name: apple_idfv
apple_idfv.description: Identifier for Vendors for Apple devices.

carrier.name: carrier
carrier.description: Carrier serivce provider used within device.

open_idfa.name: open_idfa
open_idfa.description: Identifier for Vendors for Open devices.

network_technology.name: network_technology
network_technology.description: technology used by the network provider of the device.

source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.name: com_snowplowanalytics_snowplow_geolocation_context_1
source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.description: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains geolocation data collected from the device.

root_id.name: root_id
root_id.description: The corresponding UUID used in the root table.

root_tstamp.name: root_tstamp
root_tstamp.description: The timestamp for when this event was produced.

latitude_longitude_accuracy.name: latitude_longitude_accuracy
latitude_longitude_accuracy.description: Accuracy of Latitude and Longitude coordinates for device location.

bearing.name: bearing
bearing.description: Horizontal angle between device and true north.

source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.description: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains app build and version details.

root_id.name: root_id

root_tstamp.name: root_tstamp
root_tstamp.description: The timestamp for when this event was produced.

source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.name: com_snowplowanalytics_mobile_screen_1
source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.description: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains the `screen_id` associated with a given mobile event.

root_id.name: root_id
root_id.description: The corresponding UUID used in the root table.

root_tstamp.name: root_tstamp
root_tstamp.description: The timestamp for when this event was produced.

id.name: id
id.description: A UUID for each screen e.g. `738f1fbc-5298-46fa-9474-bc0a65f014ab`.

name.name: name
name.description: The name set for a specific screen, e.g. `DemoScreenName`.

activity.name: activity
activity.description: The name of the Activity element in the screen.

fragment.name: fragment
fragment.description: The name of the screen fragment (also known as an anchor).

top_view_controller.name: top_view_controller
top_view_controller.description: The name of the root view controller.

type.name: type
type.description: The type of screen that was viewed.

view_controller.name: view_controller
view_controller.description: The name of the view controller.

source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.name: com_snowplowanalytics_snowplow_application_error_1
source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.description: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains information about any errors thrown by the application.

root_id.name: root_id
root_id.description: The corresponding UUID used in the root table.

root_tstamp.name: root_tstamp
root_tstamp.description: The timestamp for when this event was produced.

message.name: message
message.description: The error message that the application showed when the app error occurred.

programming_language.name: programming_language
programming_language.description: The name of the programming language used in which the app error occured.

class_name.name: class_name
class_name.description: The name of the class where the app error occurred.

exception_name.name: exception_name
exception_name.description: The name of the exception encountered in the app error.

is_fatal.name: is_fatal
is_fatal.description: A boolean to describe whether the app error was fatal or not.

line_number.name: line_number
line_number.description: The line number in the code where the app error occured.

stack_trace.name: stack_trace
stack_trace.description: The full stack trace that was presented when the app error occured.

thread_id.name: thread_id
thread_id.description: The ID of the thread in which the app error occurred.

thread_name.name: thread_name
thread_name.description: The name of the process that ran the thread when the app error occurred.

source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.name: com_snowplowanalytics_mobile_screen_view_1
source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.com_snowpl.description: This table contains screen view events.

root_id.name: root_id
root_id.description: The corresponding UUID used in the root table.

root_tstamp.name: root_tstamp
root_tstamp.description: The timestamp for when this event was produced.

id.name: id
id.description: The UUID of a screen view.

previous_id.name: previous_id
previous_id.description: The UUID of the previous screen view.

previous_name.name: previous_name
previous_name.description: The name of the previous screen view.

previous_type.name: previous_type
previous_type.description: The type of the previous screen viewed.

transition_type.name: transition_type
transition_type.description: The type of transition that led to the screen being viewed.

type.name: type
type.description: The type of screen that was viewed.

source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.events.name: events
source.snowplow_mobile.atomic.events.description: The `events` table contains all canonical events generated by [Snowplow's](https://snowplow.io/) trackers, including web, mobile and server side events.

app_id.name: app_id
app_id.description: Application ID e.g. `angry-birds` is used to distinguish different applications that are being tracked by the same Snowplow stack, e.g. production versus dev.

collector_tstamp.name: collector_tstamp
collector_tstamp.description: Time stamp for the event recorded by the collector e.g. `2013-11-26 00:02:05`.

dvce_created_tstamp.name: dvce_created_tstamp
dvce_created_tstamp.description: Timestamp event was recorded on the client device e.g. `2013-11-26 00:03:57.885`.

event.name: event
event.description: The type of event recorded e.g. `page_view`.

event_id.name: event_id
event_id.description: A UUID for each event e.g. `c6ef3124-b53a-4b13-a233-0088f79dcbcb`.

txn_id.name: txn_id
txn_id.description: Transaction ID set client-side, used to de-dupe records e.g. `421828`.

user_id.name: user_id
user_id.description: Unique ID set by business e.g. `jon.doe@email.com`.

user_fingerprint.name: user_fingerprint
user_fingerprint.description: A user fingerprint generated by looking at the individual browser features e.g. `2161814971`.

domain_userid.name: domain_userid
domain_userid.description: User ID set by Snowplow using 1st party cookie e.g. `bc2e92ec6c204a14`.

network_userid.name: network_userid
network_userid.description: User ID set by Snowplow using 3rd party cookie e.g. `ecdff4d0-9175-40ac-a8bb-325c49733607`.

geo_country.name: geo_country
geo_country.description: ISO 3166-1 code for the country the visitor is located in e.g. `GB`, `US`.

geo_region.name: geo_region
geo_region.description: ISO-3166-2 code for country region the visitor is in e.g. `I9`, `TX`.

geo_city.name: geo_city
geo_city.description: City the visitor is in e.g. `New York`, `London`.

geo_zipcode.name: geo_zipcode

ip_domain.name: ip_domain

page_title.name: page_title

refr_source.name: refr_source

refr_term.name: refr_term

mkt_source.name: mkt_source

mkt_term.name: mkt_term

mkt_content.name: mkt_content

se_label.name: se_label

se_property.name: se_property
se_property.description: A property associated with the object of the action e.g. `HD`, `large`.

se_value.name: se_value

tr_affiliation.name: tr_affiliation

tr_tax.name: tr_tax

ti_quantity.name: ti_quantity

pp_xoffset_min.name: pp_xoffset_min

pp_xoffset_max.name: pp_xoffset_max
pp_xoffset_max.description: Maximum page x offset seen in the last ping period e.g. `100`.

pp_yoffset_min.name: pp_yoffset_min

pp_yoffset_max.name: pp_yoffset_max

br_lang.name: br_lang

br_features_pdf.name: br_features_pdf

br_colordepth.name: br_colordepth

doc_width.name: doc_width

doc_height.name: doc_height

tr_tax_base.name: tr_tax_base

tr_shipping_base.name: tr_shipping_base

refr_dvce_tstamp.name: refr_dvce_tstamp

true_tstamp.description: User-set “true timestamp” for the event e.g. `2013-11-26 00:02:04`.

snowflake__get_catalog_tables_sql
macro.dbt_snowflake.snowflake__get_catal.macro_sql:
{% macro snowflake__get_catalog_tables_sql(information_schema) -%}
    select
        table_catalog as "table_database",
        table_schema as "table_schema",
        table_name as "table_name",
        case
            when is_dynamic = 'YES' and table_type = 'BASE TABLE' THEN 'DYNAMIC TABLE'
            else table_type
        end as "table_type",
        comment as "table_comment",

        -- note: this is the _role_ that owns the table
        table_owner as "table_owner",

        'Clustering Key' as "stats:clustering_key:label",
        clustering_key as "stats:clustering_key:value",
        'The key used to cluster this table' as "stats:clustering_key:description",
        (clustering_key is not null) as "stats:clustering_key:include",

        'Row Count' as "stats:row_count:label",
        row_count as "stats:row_count:value",
        'An approximate count of rows in this table' as "stats:row_count:description",
        (row_count is not null) as "stats:row_count:include",

        'Approximate Size' as "stats:bytes:label",
        bytes as "stats:bytes:value",
        'Approximate size of the table as reported by Snowflake' as "stats:bytes:description",
        (bytes is not null) as "stats:bytes:include",

        'Last Modified' as "stats:last_modified:label",
        to_varchar(convert_timezone('UTC', last_altered), 'yyyy-mm-dd HH24:MI'||'UTC') as "stats:last_modified:value",
        'The timestamp for last update/change' as "stats:last_modified:description",
        (last_altered is not null and table_type='BASE TABLE') as "stats:last_modified:include"
    from {{ information_schema }}.tables
{%- endmacro %}

macro.dbt_snowflake.snowflake__get_catal.name: snowflake__get_catalog_columns_sql
macro.dbt_snowflake.snowflake__get_catal.macro_sql:
{% macro snowflake__get_catalog_columns_sql(information_schema) -%}
    select
        table_catalog as "table_database",
        table_schema as "table_schema",
        table_name as "table_name",

        column_name as "column_name",
        ordinal_position as "column_index",
        data_type as "column_type",
        comment as "column_comment"
    from {{ information_schema }}.columns
{%- endmacro %}

macro.dbt.default__snapshot_staging_tabl.name: default__snapshot_staging_table
macro.dbt.default__snapshot_staging_tabl.macro_sql:
{% macro default__snapshot_staging_table(strategy, source_sql, target_relation) -%}

    with snapshot_query as (

        {{ source_sql }}

    ),

    snapshotted_data as (

        select *,
            {{ strategy.unique_key }} as dbt_unique_key

        from {{ target_relation }}
        where dbt_valid_to is null

    ),

    insertions_source_data as (

        select
            *,
            {{ strategy.unique_key }} as dbt_unique_key,
            {{ strategy.updated_at }} as dbt_updated_at,
            {{ strategy.updated_at }} as dbt_valid_from,
            nullif({{ strategy.updated_at }}, {{ strategy.updated_at }}) as dbt_valid_to,
            {{ strategy.scd_id }} as dbt_scd_id

        from snapshot_query
    ),

    updates_source_data as (

        select
            *,
            {{ strategy.unique_key }} as dbt_unique_key,
            {{ strategy.updated_at }} as dbt_updated_at,
            {{ strategy.updated_at }} as dbt_valid_from,
            {{ strategy.updated_at }} as dbt_valid_to

        from snapshot_query
    ),

    {%- if strategy.invalidate_hard_deletes %}

    deletes_source_data as (

        select
            *,
            {{ strategy.unique_key }} as dbt_unique_key
        from snapshot_query
    ),
    {% endif %}

    insertions as (

        select
            'insert' as dbt_change_type,
            source_data.*

        from insertions_source_data as source_data
        left outer join snapshotted_data on snapshotted_data.dbt_unique_key = source_data.dbt_unique_key
        where snapshotted_data.dbt_unique_key is null
           or (
                snapshotted_data.dbt_unique_key is not null
            and (
                {{ strategy.row_changed }}
            )
        )

    ),

    updates as (

        select
            'update' as dbt_change_type,
            source_data.*,
            snapshotted_data.dbt_scd_id

        from updates_source_data as source_data
        join snapshotted_data on snapshotted_data.dbt_unique_key = source_data.dbt_unique_key
        where (
            {{ strategy.row_changed }}
        )
    )

    {%- if strategy.invalidate_hard_deletes -%}
    ,

    deletes as (

        select
            'delete' as dbt_change_type,
            source_data.*,
            {{ snapshot_get_time() }} as dbt_valid_from,
            {{ snapshot_get_time() }} as dbt_updated_at,
            {{ snapshot_get_time() }} as dbt_valid_to,
            snapshotted_data.dbt_scd_id

        from snapshotted_data
        left join deletes_source_data as source_data on snapshotted_data.dbt_unique_key = source_data.dbt_unique_key
        where source_data.dbt_unique_key is null
    )
    {%- endif %}

    select * from insertions
    union all
    select * from updates
    {%- if strategy.invalidate_hard_deletes %}
    union all
    select * from deletes
    {%- endif %}

{%- endmacro %}

macro.dbt.default__snapshot_merge_sql.name: default__snapshot_merge_sql
macro.dbt.default__snapshot_merge_sql.macro_sql:
{% macro default__snapshot_merge_sql(target, source, insert_cols) -%}
    {%- set insert_cols_csv = insert_cols | join(', ') -%}

    merge into {{ target }} as DBT_INTERNAL_DEST
    using {{ source }} as DBT_INTERNAL_SOURCE
    on DBT_INTERNAL_SOURCE.dbt_scd_id = DBT_INTERNAL_DEST.dbt_scd_id

    when matched
     and DBT_INTERNAL_DEST.dbt_valid_to is null
     and DBT_INTERNAL_SOURCE.dbt_change_type in ('update', 'delete')
        then update
        set dbt_valid_to = DBT_INTERNAL_SOURCE.dbt_valid_to

    when not matched
     and DBT_INTERNAL_SOURCE.dbt_change_type = 'insert'
        then insert ({{ insert_cols_csv }})
        values ({{ insert_cols_csv }})

{% endmacro %}

macro.snowplow_utils.is_run_with_new_eve.name: is_run_with_new_events
macro.snowplow_utils.is_run_with_new_eve.description:
This macro is designed for use with Snowplow data modelling packages like `snowplow-web`. It can be used in any incremental models, to effectively block the incremental model from being updated with old data which it has already consumed. This saves cost as well as preventing historical data from being overwritten with partially complete data (due to a batch back-fill for instance).

The macro utilizes the `snowplow_[platform]_incremental_manifest` table to determine whether the model from which the macro is called, i.e. `{{ this }}`, has already consumed the data in the given run. If it has, it returns `false`. If the data in the run contains new data, `true` is returned.

For the sessions lifecycle identifier it does not use the manifest as this table is not included in it.

#### Returns

`true` if the run contains new events previously not consumed by `this`, `false` otherwise.

#### Usage

```sql

{{
config(
    materialized='incremental',
    unique_key='screen_view_id',
    upsert_date_key='start_tstamp'
)
}}

select
...

from {{ ref('snowplow_mobile_base_events_this_run' ) }}
where {{ snowplow_utils.is_run_with_new_events('snowplow_mobile') }} --returns false if run doesn't contain new events.

```

arguments.name: package_name
arguments.description: The modeling package name e.g. `snowplow-mobile`

macro.snowplow_utils.get_sde_or_context.name: get_sde_or_context
macro.snowplow_utils.get_sde_or_context.description:
This macro exists for Redshift and Postgres users to more easily select their self-describing event and context tables and apply de-duplication before joining onto their (already de-duplicated) events table. The `root_id` and `root_tstamp` columns are by default returned as `schema_name_id` and `schema_name_tstamp` respectively, where `schema_name` is the value in the `schema_name` column of the table. In the case where multiple entities may be sent in the context (e.g. products in a search results), you should set the `single_entity` argument to `false` and use an additional criteria in your join (see [the snowplow docs](https://docs.snowplow.io/docs/modeling-your-data/modeling-your-data-with-dbt/dbt-advanced-usage/dbt-duplicates/) for further details).

Note that is the responsibility of the user to ensure they have no duplicate names when using this macro multiple times or when a schema column name matches on already in the events table. In this case the `prefix` argument should be used and aliasing applied to the output.

#### Returns

CTE sql for deduplicating records from the schema table, without the schema details columns. The final CTE is the name of the original table.

#### Usage

With at most one entity per context:
```sql
with {{ snowplow_utils.get_sde_or_context('atomic', 'nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1', "'2023-01-01'", "'2023-02-01'")}}

select
...
from my_events_table a
left join nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1 b on 
    a.event_id = b.yauaa_context__id 
    and a.collector_tstamp = b.yauaa_context__tstamp
```
With the possibility of multiple entities per context, your events table must already be de-duped but still have a field with the number of duplicates:
```sql
with {{ snowplow_utils.get_sde_or_context('atomic', 'nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1', "'2023-01-01'", "'2023-02-01'", single_entity = false)}}

select
...,
count(*) over (partition by a.event_id) as duplicate_count
from my_events_table a
left join nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1 b on 
    a.event_id = b.yauaa_context__id 
    and a.collector_tstamp = b.yauaa_context__tstamp
    and mod(b.yauaa_context__index, a.duplicate_count) = 0
```

arguments.name: schema
arguments.description: The schema your context or sde table is in

arguments.name: identifier
arguments.description: The table name of your context or sde

arguments.name: lower_limit
arguments.description: Lower limit to filter the `root_tstamp` field on, only used if both lower and upper are provided

arguments.name: upper_limit
arguments.description: Upper limit to filter the `root_tstamp` field on, only used if both lower and upper are provided

arguments.name: prefix
arguments.description: A string to prefix (additional `_` added automatically) the column names with. If not provided `root_id` and `root_tstamp` will be prefixed with the schema name.

macro.snowplow_utils.get_value_by_target.description:
This macro is designed to dynamically return values based on the target (`target.name`) you are running against. Your target names are defined in your [profiles.yml](https://docs.getdbt.com/reference/profiles.yml) file. This can be useful for dynamically changing variables within your project, depending on whether you are running in dev or prod.

#### Returns

The value relevant to the target environment

#### Usage

```yml

# dbt_project.yml
...
vars:
snowplow_web:
    snowplow__backfill_limit_days: "{{ snowplow_utils.get_value_by_target(dev_value=1, default_value=30, dev_target_name='dev') }}"

```

arguments.name: dev_value
arguments.description: Value to use if target is development

arguments.name: default_value
arguments.description: Value to use if target is not development

arguments.name: dev_target_name
arguments.description: (Optional) Name of the development target. Default `dev`

macro.snowplow_utils.n_timedeltas_ago.name: n_timedeltas_ago
macro.snowplow_utils.n_timedeltas_ago.description:
This macro takes the current timestamp and subtracts `n` units, as defined by the `timedelta_attribute`, from it. This is achieved using the Python datetime module, rather than querying your database. By combining this with the `get_value_by_target` macro, you can dynamically set dates depending on your environment.

#### Returns

Current timestamp minus `n` units.

#### Usage

```sql

{{ snowplow_utils.n_timedeltas_ago(1, 'weeks') }}

```

arguments.name: n
arguments.description: The number of timedeltas to subtract from the current timestamp

arguments.name: timedelta_attribute
arguments.description: The type of units to subtract. This can be any valid attribute of the [timedelta](https://docs.python.org/3/library/datetime.html#timedelta-objects) object

macro.snowplow_utils.get_columns_in_rela.name: get_columns_in_relation_by_column_prefix
macro.snowplow_utils.get_columns_in_rela.description:
This macro returns an array of column objects within a relation that start with the given column prefix. This is useful when you have multiple versions of a column within a table and want to dynamically identify all versions.

#### Returns

An array of (column objects)[https://docs.getdbt.com/reference/dbt-classes#column]. The name of each column can be accessed with the name property.

#### Usage

```sql
get_columns_in_relation_by_column_prefix(ref('snowplow_web_base_events_this_run'), 'domain')

-- returns
['domain_sessionid', 'domain_userid', 'domain_sessionidx',...]

{% set matched_columns = snowplow_utils.get_columns_in_relation_by_column_prefix(
                    relation=ref('snowplow_web_base_events_this_run'),
                    column_prefix='custom_context_1_0_'
                    ) %}

{% for column in matched_columns %}
{{ column.name }}
{% endfor %}

# Renders to something like:
'custom_context_1_0_1'
'custom_context_1_0_2'
'custom_context_1_0_3'

```

arguments.name: relation
arguments.description: A table or `ref` type object to get the columns from

arguments.name: column_prefix
arguments.description: The prefix string to search for matching columns

macro.snowplow_utils.get_field.name: get_field
macro.snowplow_utils.get_field.description:
This macro exists to make it easier to extract a field from our `unstruct_` and `contexts_` type columns for users in Snowflake, Databricks, and BigQuery (using a wildcard version number is only possible for BigQuery e.g. `column_name = 'contexts_nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1_*'`). The macro can handle type casting and selecting from arrays.

#### Returns

SQL snippet to select the field specified from the column

#### Usage

Extracting a single field
```sql

select
{{ snowplow_utils.get_field(column_name = 'contexts_nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1', 
                            field_name = 'agent_class', 
                            table_alias = 'a',
                            type = 'string',
                            array_index = 0)}} as yauaa_agent_class
from 
    my_events_table a

```

Extracting multiple fields
```sql

select
{% for field in [('field1', 'string'), ('field2', 'numeric'), ...] %}
  {{ snowplow_utils.get_field(column_name = 'contexts_nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1', 
                            field_name = field[0], 
                            table_alias = 'a',
                            type = field[1],
                            array_index = 0)}} as {{ field[0] }}
{% endfor %}

from 
    my_events_table a

```

arguments.name: column_name
arguments.description: Name of the column to extract the field from

arguments.name: field_name
arguments.description: Name of the field to extract

arguments.name: table_alias
arguments.description: (Optional) Alias of the table in your query that the column exists in. Default `none` (no table alias)

arguments.name: type
arguments.description: (Optional) Type to cast the field to if required. Default `none` (no casting)

arguments.name: array_index
arguments.description: (Optional) Index of the array to select in case of multiple entries. Uses `SAFE_OFFSET` for BigQuery. Default `none` (not an array)

This macro takes care of harmonising cross-db split to array type functions. The macro supports a custom delimiter if your string is not delimited by a comma with no space (default).

#### Returns

The data warehouse appropriate sql to perform a split to array. 

#### Usage

```sql
select
...
{{ snowplow_utils.get_split_to_array('my_string_column', 'a', ', ') }}
...
from ... a

```

arguments.name: string_column
arguments.description: Name of the column to split into an array

arguments.name: column_prefix
arguments.description: Table alias for the string_column

arguments.name: delimiter
arguments.description: (Optional) String that determines how to split your string. Default ','

macro.snowplow_utils.get_string_agg.name: get_string_agg
macro.snowplow_utils.get_string_agg.description:
This macro takes care of harmonising cross-db `list_agg`, `string_agg` type functions. These are aggregate functions (i.e. to be used with a `group by`) that take values from grouped rows and concatenates them into a single string. This macro supports ordering values by an arbitrary column and ensuring unique values (i.e. applying distinct).

Note that databricks does not have list/string_agg function so a more complex expression is used.

#### Returns

The data warehouse appropriate sql to perform a list/string_agg. 

#### Usage

```sql
select
...
{{ snowplow_utils.get_string_agg('base_column', 'column_prefix', ';', 'order_by_col', sort_numeric=true, order_by_column_prefix='order_by_column_prefix', is_distict=True, order_desc=True)  }},
...
from ...
group by ...

```

arguments.name: base_column
arguments.description: Name of the column to aggregate values for

arguments.name: column_prefix
arguments.description: Table alias for the base_column

arguments.name: separator
arguments.description: (Optional) String to use to separate your values. Default ','

arguments.name: order_by_column
arguments.description: (Optional) Column to order your values by before aggregating. Default base_column

arguments.name: sort_numeric
arguments.description: (Optional) Is the column you are ordering by a numeric value (regardless of stored type). Default false

arguments.name: order_by_column_prefix
arguments.description: (Optional) Table alias for the order_by_column. Default column_prefix

arguments.name: is_distinct
arguments.description: (Optional) Do you want to apply distinct to your values. Will be applied after ordering. Default false

arguments.name: order_desc
arguments.description: (Optional) Do you wish to apply the ordering descending. Default false

doc.dbt.__overview__.name: __overview__
doc.dbt.__overview__.block_contents:
### Welcome!

Welcome to the auto-generated documentation for your dbt project!

### Navigation

You can use the `Project` and `Database` navigation tabs on the left side of the window to explore the models
in your project.

#### Project Tab
The `Project` tab mirrors the directory structure of your dbt project. In this tab, you can see all of the
models defined in your dbt project, as well as models imported from dbt packages.

#### Database Tab
The `Database` tab also exposes your models, but in a format that looks more like a database explorer. This view
shows relations (tables and views) grouped into database schemas. Note that ephemeral models are _not_ shown
in this interface, as they do not exist in the database.

### Graph Exploration
You can click the blue icon on the bottom-right corner of the page to view the lineage graph of your models.

On model pages, you'll see the immediate parents and children of the model you're exploring. By clicking the `Expand`
button at the top-right of this lineage pane, you'll be able to see all of the models that are used to build,
or are built from, the model you're exploring.

Once expanded, you'll be able to use the `--select` and `--exclude` model selection syntax to filter the
models in the graph. For more information on model selection, check out the [dbt docs](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/model-selection-syntax).

Note that you can also right-click on models to interactively filter and explore the graph.

---

### More information

- [What is dbt](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/introduction)?
- Read the [dbt viewpoint](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/viewpoint)
- [Installation](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/installation)
- Join the [dbt Community](https://www.getdbt.com/community/) for questions and discussion

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_app_id.name: col_app_id
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_app_id.block_contents: Application ID e.g. `angry-birds` is used to distinguish different applications that are being tracked by the same Snowplow stack, e.g. production versus dev.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_collector_tstamp.name: col_collector_tstamp
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_collector_tstamp.block_contents: Time stamp for the event recorded by the collector e.g. `2013-11-26 00:02:05`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_dvce_created_tst.name: col_dvce_created_tstamp
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_dvce_created_tst.block_contents: Timestamp event was recorded on the client device e.g. `2013-11-26 00:03:57.885`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_event.name: col_event
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_event.block_contents: The type of event recorded e.g. `page_view`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_event_id.name: col_event_id
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_event_id.block_contents: A UUID for each event e.g. `c6ef3124-b53a-4b13-a233-0088f79dcbcb`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_txn_id.name: col_txn_id
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_txn_id.block_contents: Transaction ID set client-side, used to de-dupe records e.g. `421828`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_user_id.name: col_user_id
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_user_id.block_contents: Unique ID set by business e.g. `jon.doe@email.com`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_user_fingerprint.name: col_user_fingerprint
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_user_fingerprint.block_contents: A user fingerprint generated by looking at the individual browser features e.g. `2161814971`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_domain_userid.name: col_domain_userid
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_domain_userid.block_contents: User ID set by Snowplow using 1st party cookie e.g. `bc2e92ec6c204a14`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_previous_session.name: col_previous_session_id
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_previous_session.block_contents: A previous visit / session index e.g. `3`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_first_event_id.name: col_first_event_id
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_first_event_id.block_contents: The event ID of the first event.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_session_first_ev.name: col_session_first_event_id
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_session_first_ev.block_contents: A first visit / session index e.g. `3`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_session_last_eve.name: col_session_last_event_id
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_session_last_eve.block_contents: A last visit / session index e.g. `3`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_network_userid.name: col_network_userid
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_network_userid.block_contents: User ID set by Snowplow using 3rd party cookie e.g. `ecdff4d0-9175-40ac-a8bb-325c49733607`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_geo_country.name: col_geo_country
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_geo_country.block_contents: ISO 3166-1 code for the country the visitor is located in e.g. `GB`, `US`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_geo_region.name: col_geo_region
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_geo_region.block_contents: ISO-3166-2 code for country region the visitor is in e.g. `I9`, `TX`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_geo_city.name: col_geo_city
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_geo_city.block_contents: City the visitor is in e.g. `New York`, `London`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_geo_zipcode.name: col_geo_zipcode
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_geo_zipcode.block_contents: Postcode the visitor is in e.g. `94109`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_ip_organization.name: col_ip_organization
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_ip_organization.block_contents: Organization associated with the visitor's IP address - defaults to ISP name if none is found e.g. `Bouygues Telecom`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_ip_domain.name: col_ip_domain
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_ip_domain.block_contents: Second level domain name associated with the visitor's IP address e.g. `nuvox.net`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_page_title.name: col_page_title
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_page_title.block_contents: Web page title e.g. `Snowplow Docs - Understanding the structure of Snowplow data`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_refr_source.name: col_refr_source
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_refr_source.block_contents: Name of referer if recognised e.g. `Bing images`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_refr_term.name: col_refr_term
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_refr_term.block_contents: Keywords if source is a search engine e.g. `psychic oracle cards`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_mkt_source.name: col_mkt_source
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_mkt_source.block_contents: The company / website where the traffic came from e.g. `Google`, `Facebook`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_mkt_term.name: col_mkt_term
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_mkt_term.block_contents: Any keywords associated with the referrer e.g. `new age tarot decks`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_mkt_content.name: col_mkt_content
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_mkt_content.block_contents: The content of the ad. (Or an ID so that it can be looked up.) e.g. `13894723`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_se_label.name: col_se_label
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_se_label.block_contents: The object of the action e.g. the ID of the video played or SKU of the product added-to-basket e.g. `pbz00123`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_se_property.name: col_se_property
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_se_property.block_contents: A property associated with the object of the action e.g. `HD`, `large`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_se_value.name: col_se_value
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_se_value.block_contents: A value associated with the event / action e.g. the value of goods added-to-basket e.g. `9.99`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_tr_affiliation.name: col_tr_affiliation
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_tr_affiliation.block_contents: Transaction affiliation (e.g. store where sale took place) e.g. `web`.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_tr_tax.name: col_tr_tax

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_sessions_.name: table_base_sessions_lifecycle_manifest
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_sessions_.block_contents:
This incremental table is a manifest of all sessions that have been processed by the Snowplow dbt mobile model. For each session, the start and end timestamp is recorded.

By knowing the life-cycle of a session the model is able to able to determine which sessions and thus events to process for a given time-frame, as well as the complete date range required to reprocess all events of each session.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_new_event.name: table_base_new_event_limits
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_new_event.block_contents:
This table contains the lower and upper timestamp limits for the given run of the mobile model. These limits are used to select new events from the events table.

The sql to determine the correct limits for the run is generated by the `get_run_limits()` macro. Please refer to the documentation for details on how this macro determines the run limits.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_events_th.name: table_base_events_this_run
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_events_th.block_contents:
For any given run, this table contains all required events to be consumed by subsequent nodes in the Snowplow dbt mob package. This is a cleaned, de-duped dataset, containing all columns from the raw events table as well as having various optional contexts joined-on/unpacked.

**Note: This table should be used as the input to any custom modules that require event level data, rather than selecting straight from `atomic.events`**

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_events_ru.name: table_base_events_run_limits
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_events_ru.block_contents: This table contains the lower and upper timestamp limits for the given run of the mobile model. These limits are used to select new events from the events table. These limits are determined by taking the `MIN` of the `start_tstamp` and `MAX` of the `end_tstamp` from the `snowplow_mobile_base_sessions_this_run` table for the `lower_limit` and `upper_limit` respectively.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_sessions_.name: table_base_sessions_this_run
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_sessions_.block_contents: For any given run, this table contains all the required sessions.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_increment.name: table_base_incremental_manifest
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_increment.block_contents: This incremental table is a manifest of the timestamp of the latest event consumed per model within the `snowplow-mobile` package as well as any models leveraging the incremental framework provided by the package. The latest event's timestamp is based off `collector_tstamp`. This table is used to determine what events should be processed in the next run of the model.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_session_contex.name: table_session_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_session_contex.block_contents: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains the `session_id` associated with a given mobile event.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_mobile_context.name: table_mobile_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_mobile_context.block_contents: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains various mobile device details and identifiers.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_geolocation_co.name: table_geolocation_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_geolocation_co.block_contents: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains geolocation data collected from the device.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_app_context.name: table_app_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_app_context.block_contents: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains app build and version details.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_screen_context.name: table_screen_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_screen_context.block_contents: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains the `screen_id` associated with a given mobile event.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_app_errors_con.name: table_app_errors_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_app_errors_con.block_contents: **Redshift and Postgres only**. This context table contains information about any errors thrown by the application.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_screen_view_ev.name: table_screen_view_events
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_screen_view_ev.block_contents: This table contains screen view events.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_events.name: table_events
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_events.block_contents: The `events` table contains all canonical events generated by [Snowplow's](https://snowplow.io/) trackers, including web, mobile and server side events.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_app_errors.name: table_app_errors
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_app_errors.block_contents: This derived table contains all app errors and should be the end point for any analysis or BI tools looking to investigate app errors. This is an optional table that will be empty if the `app_errors` module is not enabled.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_app_errors_thi.name: table_app_errors_this_run
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_app_errors_thi.block_contents: This staging table contains all the app errors for the given run of the Mobile model. This is an optional table that will not be generated if the `app_errors` module is not enabled.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_message.name: col_message

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_class_name.name: col_class_name

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_exception_name.name: col_exception_name

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_is_fatal.name: col_is_fatal

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_line_number.name: col_line_number

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_stack_trace.name: col_stack_trace

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_thread_name.name: col_thread_name
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_thread_name.block_contents: The name of the process that ran the thread when the app error occurred.

doc.snowplow_mobile.col_event_index_in_s.name: col_event_index_in_session
doc.snowplow_mobile.col_event_index_in_s.block_contents: A session index of the event.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_app_conte.name: table_base_app_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_app_conte.block_contents:
** This table only exists when working in a Redshift or Postgres warehouse. **

This optional table provides extra context on an event level and brings in data surrounding the application's build and version.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_geo_conte.name: table_base_geo_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_geo_conte.block_contents:
** This table only exists when working in a Redshift or Postgres warehouse. **

This optional table provides extra context on an event level and brings in data surrounding a device's geographical properties, such as latitude/longitude, altitude, and speed.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_mobile_co.name: table_base_mobile_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_mobile_co.block_contents:
** This table only exists when working in a Redshift or Postgres warehouse. **

This optional table provides extra context on an event level and brings in data surrounding a device's manufacturer, model, and carrier.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_screen_co.name: table_base_screen_context
doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_screen_co.block_contents:
** This table only exists when working in a Redshift or Postgres warehouse. **

This optional table provides extra context on an event level and brings in data surrounding the screen that the application is on, such as the screen's id, activity, and type.

doc.snowplow_mobile.table_base_session_c.name: table_base_session_context

doc.snowplow_mobile.__snowplow_mobile__.name: __snowplow_mobile__
doc.snowplow_mobile.__snowplow_mobile__.block_contents:
# Snowplow Mobile Package

Welcome to the model documentation site for the Snowplow mobile dbt package. The package contains a fully incremental model, that transforms raw mobile event data generated by the [Snowplow iOS][ios-tracker] or [android trackers][android-tracker] into a series of derived tables of varying levels of aggregation.

**For more information, including a QuickStart guide, operation and configuration, and implementing your own custom modules on top of this please visit the [Snowplow Docs](https://docs.snowplow.io/docs/modeling-your-data/modeling-your-data-with-dbt/).**

*Note this model design doc site is linked to latest release of the package. If you are not using the latest release, [generate and serve](https://docs.getdbt.com/reference/commands/cmd-docs#dbt-docs-serve) the doc site locally for accurate documentation.*

## Overview

This model consists of a series of modules, each producing a table which serves as the input to the next module. The 'standard' modules are:

- Base: Performs the incremental logic, outputting the table `snowplow_mobile_base_events_this_run` which contains a de-duped data set of all events required for the current run of the model.
- Screen Views: Aggregates event level data to a screen view level, on `screen_view_id`.
- Sessions: Aggregates screen view level data to a session level, on `session_id`.
- Users: Aggregates session level data to a users level, on `device_user_id`.
- User Mapping: Provides a mapping between user identifiers, `device_user_id` and `user_id`. This can be used for session stitching.

Each module produces a table which acts as the input to the subsequent module (the `_this_run` tables), and updates a derived table - with the exception of the Base module, which takes atomic data as its input, and does not update a derived table.

## Installation

Check [dbt Hub](https://hub.getdbt.com/snowplow/snowplow_mobile/latest/) for the latest installation instructions, or read the [dbt docs][dbt-package-docs] for more information on installing packages.

# Join the Snowplow community

We welcome all ideas, questions and contributions!

For support requests, please use our community support [Discourse][discourse] forum.

If you find a bug, please report an issue on GitHub.

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_app_id_filter.name: macro_app_id_filter
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_app_id_filter.block_contents:
Generates a `sql` filter for the values in `app_ids` applied on the `app_id` column.

#### Returns

`app_id in (...)` if any `app_ids` are provided, otherwise `true`.

#### Usage

```sql
app_id_filter(['web', 'mobile', 'news'])

-- returns
app_id in ('web', 'mobile', 'news')
```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_columns_in_.name: macro_get_columns_in_relation_by_column_prefix
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_columns_in_.block_contents:
This macro returns an array of column objects within a relation that start with the given column prefix. This is useful when you have multiple versions of a column within a table and want to dynamically identify all versions.

#### Returns

An array of (column objects)[https://docs.getdbt.com/reference/dbt-classes#column]. The name of each column can be accessed with the name property.

#### Usage

```sql
get_columns_in_relation_by_column_prefix(ref('snowplow_web_base_events_this_run'), 'domain')

-- returns
['domain_sessionid', 'domain_userid', 'domain_sessionidx',...]

{% set matched_columns = snowplow_utils.get_columns_in_relation_by_column_prefix(
                    relation=ref('snowplow_web_base_events_this_run'),
                    column_prefix='custom_context_1_0_'
                    ) %}

{% for column in matched_columns %}
{{ column.name }}
{% endfor %}

# Renders to something like:
'custom_context_1_0_1'
'custom_context_1_0_2'
'custom_context_1_0_3'

```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_schemas_by_.name: macro_get_schemas_by_pattern
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_schemas_by_.block_contents:
Given a pattern, finds and returns all schemas that match that pattern. Note that for databricks any single character matches (`_`) will not be properly translated due to databricks using a regex expression instead of a SQL `like` clause.

      #### Returns

      A list of schemas that match the pattern provided.

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_value_by_ta.name: macro_get_value_by_target_type
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_value_by_ta.block_contents:
Returns the value provided based on the `target.type`. This is useful when you need a different value based on which warehouse is being used e.g. cluster fields or partition keys.

#### Returns

The appropriate value for the target warehouse type, or an error if not an expected target type.

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_value_by_ta.name: macro_get_value_by_target
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_value_by_ta.block_contents:
This macro is designed to dynamically return values based on the target (`target.name`) you are running against. Your target names are defined in your [profiles.yml](https://docs.getdbt.com/reference/profiles.yml) file. This can be useful for dynamically changing variables within your project, depending on whether you are running in dev or prod.

#### Returns

The value relevant to the target environment

#### Usage

```yml

# dbt_project.yml
...
vars:
snowplow_web:
    snowplow__backfill_limit_days: "{{ snowplow_utils.get_value_by_target(dev_value=1, default_value=30, dev_target_name='dev') }}"

```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_is_run_with_new.name: macro_is_run_with_new_events
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_is_run_with_new.block_contents:
This macro is designed for use with Snowplow data modelling packages like `snowplow-web`. It can be used in any incremental models, to effectively block the incremental model from being updated with old data which it has already consumed. This saves cost as well as preventing historical data from being overwritten with partially complete data (due to a batch back-fill for instance).

The macro utilizes the `snowplow_[platform]_incremental_manifest` table to determine whether the model from which the macro is called, i.e. `{{ this }}`, has already consumed the data in the given run. If it has, it returns `false`. If the data in the run contains new data, `true` is returned.

For the sessions lifecycle identifier it does not use the manifest as this table is not included in it.

#### Returns

`true` if the run contains new events previously not consumed by `this`, `false` otherwise.

#### Usage

```sql

{{
config(
    materialized='incremental',
    unique_key='screen_view_id',
    upsert_date_key='start_tstamp'
)
}}

select
...

from {{ ref('snowplow_mobile_base_events_this_run' ) }}
where {{ snowplow_utils.is_run_with_new_events('snowplow_mobile') }} --returns false if run doesn't contain new events.

```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_set_query_tag.name: macro_set_query_tag
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_set_query_tag.block_contents:
This macro takes a provided statement as argument and generates the SQL command to set this statement as the query_tag for Snowflake databases, and does nothing otherwise. It can be used to safely set the query_tag regardless of database type.

#### Returns

An alter session command set to the `query_tag` to the `statement` for Snowflake, otherwise nothing

#### Usage

```sql

{{ snowplow_utils.set_query_tag('snowplow_query_tag') }}

```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_n_timedeltas_ag.name: macro_n_timedeltas_ago
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_n_timedeltas_ag.block_contents:
This macro takes the current timestamp and subtracts `n` units, as defined by the `timedelta_attribute`, from it. This is achieved using the Python datetime module, rather than querying your database. By combining this with the `get_value_by_target` macro, you can dynamically set dates depending on your environment.

#### Returns

Current timestamp minus `n` units.

#### Usage

```sql

{{ snowplow_utils.n_timedeltas_ago(1, 'weeks') }}

```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_string_agg.name: macro_get_string_agg
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_string_agg.block_contents:
This macro takes care of harmonising cross-db `list_agg`, `string_agg` type functions. These are aggregate functions (i.e. to be used with a `group by`) that take values from grouped rows and concatenates them into a single string. This macro supports ordering values by an arbitrary column and ensuring unique values (i.e. applying distinct).

Note that databricks does not have list/string_agg function so a more complex expression is used.

#### Returns

The data warehouse appropriate sql to perform a list/string_agg. 

#### Usage

```sql
select
...
{{ snowplow_utils.get_string_agg('base_column', 'column_prefix', ';', 'order_by_col', sort_numeric=true, order_by_column_prefix='order_by_column_prefix', is_distict=True, order_desc=True)  }},
...
from ...
group by ...

```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_split_to_ar.name: macro_get_split_to_array
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_split_to_ar.block_contents:
This macro takes care of harmonising cross-db split to array type functions. The macro supports a custom delimiter if your string is not delimited by a comma with no space (default).

#### Returns

The data warehouse appropriate sql to perform a split to array. 

#### Usage

```sql
select
...
{{ snowplow_utils.get_split_to_array('my_string_column', 'a', ', ') }}
...
from ... a

```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_array_to_st.name: macro_get_array_to_string
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_array_to_st.block_contents:
This macro takes care of harmonising cross-db array to string type functions. The macro supports a custom delimiter if you don't want to use a comma with no space (default).

#### Returns

The data warehouse appropriate sql to convert an array to a string. 

#### Usage

```sql
select
...
{{ snowplow_utils.get_array_to_string('my_array_column', 'a', ', ') }}
...
from ... a

```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_sde_or_cont.name: macro_get_sde_or_context
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_sde_or_cont.block_contents:
This macro exists for Redshift and Postgres users to more easily select their self-describing event and context tables and apply de-duplication before joining onto their (already de-duplicated) events table. The `root_id` and `root_tstamp` columns are by default returned as `schema_name_id` and `schema_name_tstamp` respectively, where `schema_name` is the value in the `schema_name` column of the table. In the case where multiple entities may be sent in the context (e.g. products in a search results), you should set the `single_entity` argument to `false` and use an additional criteria in your join (see [the snowplow docs](https://docs.snowplow.io/docs/modeling-your-data/modeling-your-data-with-dbt/dbt-advanced-usage/dbt-duplicates/) for further details).

Note that is the responsibility of the user to ensure they have no duplicate names when using this macro multiple times or when a schema column name matches on already in the events table. In this case the `prefix` argument should be used and aliasing applied to the output.

#### Returns

CTE sql for deduplicating records from the schema table, without the schema details columns. The final CTE is the name of the original table.

#### Usage

With at most one entity per context:
```sql
with {{ snowplow_utils.get_sde_or_context('atomic', 'nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1', "'2023-01-01'", "'2023-02-01'")}}

select
...
from my_events_table a
left join nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1 b on 
    a.event_id = b.yauaa_context__id 
    and a.collector_tstamp = b.yauaa_context__tstamp
```
With the possibility of multiple entities per context, your events table must already be de-duped but still have a field with the number of duplicates:
```sql
with {{ snowplow_utils.get_sde_or_context('atomic', 'nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1', "'2023-01-01'", "'2023-02-01'", single_entity = false)}}

select
...,
count(*) over (partition by a.event_id) as duplicate_count
from my_events_table a
left join nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1 b on 
    a.event_id = b.yauaa_context__id 
    and a.collector_tstamp = b.yauaa_context__tstamp
    and mod(b.yauaa_context__index, a.duplicate_count) = 0
```

doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_field.name: macro_get_field
doc.snowplow_utils.macro_get_field.block_contents:
This macro exists to make it easier to extract a field from our `unstruct_` and `contexts_` type columns for users in Snowflake, Databricks, and BigQuery (using a wildcard version number is only possible for BigQuery e.g. `column_name = 'contexts_nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1_*'`). The macro can handle type casting and selecting from arrays.

#### Returns

SQL snippet to select the field specified from the column

#### Usage

Extracting a single field
```sql

select
{{ snowplow_utils.get_field(column_name = 'contexts_nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1', 
                            field_name = 'agent_class', 
                            table_alias = 'a',
                            type = 'string',
                            array_index = 0)}} as yauaa_agent_class
from 
    my_events_table a

```

Extracting multiple fields
```sql

select
{% for field in [('field1', 'string'), ('field2', 'numeric'), ...] %}
  {{ snowplow_utils.get_field(column_name = 'contexts_nl_basjes_yauaa_context_1', 
                            field_name = field[0], 
                            table_alias = 'a',
                            type = field[1],
                            array_index = 0)}} as {{ field[0] }}
{% endfor %}

from 
    my_events_table a

```

model.snowplow_mobile_integration_tests..name: snowplow_mobile_ses_goals
model.snowplow_mobile_integration_tests..raw_code:
{#
Copyright (c) 2021-present Snowplow Analytics Ltd. All rights reserved.
This program is licensed to you under the Snowplow Community License Version 1.0,
and you may not use this file except in compliance with the Snowplow Community License Version 1.0.
You may obtain a copy of the Snowplow Community License Version 1.0 at https://docs.snowplow.io/community-license-1.0
#}

{{
  config(
    materialized='incremental',
    enabled=var('snowplow__enable_custom_example'),
    unique_key='max_tstamp',
    upsert_date_key='max_tstamp',
    sort='max_tstamp',
    dist='session_id',
    partition_by = snowplow_utils.get_value_by_target_type(bigquery_val= {
      "field": "max_tstamp",
      "data_type": "timestamp"
    }),
    cluster_by=["session_id"],
    snowplow_optimize=true
  )
}}

with goals as (
    select
        sv.session_id,
        MAX(sv.derived_tstamp) as max_tstamp,
        {{ snowplow_mobile.bool_or("sv.screen_view_name = 'registration'") }} AS has_started_registration,
        {{ snowplow_mobile.bool_or("sv.screen_view_name = 'my_account'") }} AS has_completed_registration,
        {{ snowplow_mobile.bool_or("sv.screen_view_name = 'search_results'") }} AS has_used_search,
        {{ snowplow_mobile.bool_or("sv.screen_view_name = 'products'") }} AS has_viewed_products

    from {{ ref('snowplow_mobile_screen_views_this_run' ) }} sv
    group by 1
)

select
    g.session_id,
    g.max_tstamp,
    g.has_started_registration,
    g.has_completed_registration,
    g.has_used_search,
    g.has_viewed_products,
    case
        when g.has_started_registration and g.has_completed_registration
            and g.has_used_search and g.has_viewed_products then TRUE
    else FALSE end as has_completed_goals

from goals g
